history.subject: Inquiry on further python study
history.content: I wonder how I can continue further python study if I'm not able to take 148 (possible only during summer so I'm not so sure). Any online material or something suggested? Thanks to your teaching, I really find python very fun!

Codecademy comes to mind, but it really only teaches you the basics, which is similar to what we have been taught already.

Codewars is a great platform for attempting to solve challenges using a programming language of your choice.

But in my personal opinion, the best way to learn more about the language is to build something with it. When working on projects, you'll generally become stuck if you don't understand a certain concept, or you continually optimize your programs based on things you learn. Along the way, you'll most likely learn how to use popular libraries, improve readability, and understand better methods of debugging. Plus, you get to make something by yourself (or with a team of others), something you can be proud of.

So go ahead, ask questions, look at the open source projects of others (on GitHub for example) and have some fun with the language!

history.subject: what's the relationship between sys and wing?

history.content:
sys is a python module while wing is an IDE. 

sys is used by "interpreter" programs which is contained within an IDE. 

An IDE is something that puts together all aspects of programming into an easy, convenient window (the part where you write a file and execute it. Usually the command prompt is used to execute such files because there is no "console" for a text editor)

Importing sys can help you interact with the interpreter and change stuff like "recursion limit" (read about recursive algorithms to understand this) and much more so that you have control on how the program is executed.

history.subject: Return value of list.pop() within a method
history.content:
I notice that there is a difference between when I call list.pop() within a method vs. within just the python shell. When I call a method containing list.pop() within it, it does remove the object at list[-1], but I do not see the value printed within the python shell and it instead returns NoneType. However, if I call list.pop() in the python shell, I do get a value returned.

I understand that to get a value returned when I cal list.pop() in a method, I have to write return list.pop(). However, I do not understand why this is the case and I am confused because my belief is that list.pop() itself is supposed to return something other than NoneType. 

Could someone please explain the difference to me? Thank you.

Remember, that when you type a line of code into the shell, it displays the output to the screen.

But when you run your code, it only displays any values you have it print.

One quick example - note that nothing is displayed when you execute an assignment statement in the shell.

>>> lst = [1,2,3]
>>> lst.pop() #returned value from pop() gets displayed
3
>>> x = lst.pop() #returned value not displayed since assigned to x
>>> x
2

history.subject: EXAM question on range
history.content: can some explain he answer to this. Thanks

The first for loop is running from 0 to 1 (because 2 is not inclusive) and the inner for loop is also running from 0 to 1. So total of 4 iterations.
First it will print (0,0)
Then (0,1)
Then (1,0)
And lastly (1,1)
